In [ ]:
# run_app(df)
  • Higher the effort category lower is the loss of coins.
  • government sector service and private sector service have lost most of the coins.
  • Higher the pier category (1,2,3), higher the loss of coins
  • Accounts of Scheduled Private banks and Scheduled PSUs have the highest loss of coins
  • Medium effort category people tend to start as well as complete more number of games
  • People belonging to Private sector service, Govt sector service, Business, Housewives, and 0 tend to start and complete more number of games than others
  • tier 2 category tend to complete more number of games whereas tier 3 category tend to start more number of games
  • people belonging to Scheduled Private banks and Scheduled PSUs tend to complete and start more number of games

def deviance(X, y, model):
    return 2*log_loss(y, model.predict_proba(X), normalize=False)

def log_reg_cv(train_X,train_Y,feature_list):
    f1_list_train=[]
    f1_list_test=[]
    acc_list_train=[]
    acc_list_test=[]
    for i in range(1,len(feature_list)+1):
        cv_results_temp = cross_validate(LogReg(random_state=48,solver='liblinear',penalty="l1"),
                                         train_X.loc[:,feature_list[:i]],train_Y, 
                            cv=5,scoring=["accuracy","f1"],return_train_score=True)
        mean_acc_train=np.mean(cv_results_temp["train_accuracy"])
        mean_f1_train=np.mean(cv_results_temp["train_f1"])
        mean_acc_test=np.mean(cv_results_temp["test_accuracy"])
        mean_f1_test=np.mean(cv_results_temp["test_f1"])
        f1_list_train.append(mean_f1_train)
        acc_list_train.append(mean_acc_train)
        f1_list_test.append(mean_f1_test)
        acc_list_test.append(mean_acc_test)
    cv_scoring_df=pd.DataFrame(zip(f1_list_train,f1_list_test,acc_list_train,acc_list_test))
    cv_scoring_df.columns=["Mean F1 Train","Mean F1 Test","Mean Accuracy Train","Mean Accuracy Test"]
    cv_scoring_df.index=cv_scoring_df.index+1
    return cv_scoring_df

A for loop is used for forward selection to determine the number of features to be used using a logistic regression with L1 penalty, a LASSO logistic regression. 2 dataframes will be generated to determine which feature ranking is more suitable for the model based on F1 and accuracy scores.¶

In [67]:
def dtree_cv(train_X, train_Y, feature_list, n):
    f1_list_train=[]
    f1_list_test=[]
    acc_list_train=[]
    acc_list_test=[]
    cv_results_temp = cross_validate(dtree_clf(max_depth=4, max_features=5, min_samples_leaf=10,min_samples_split=5,random_state=48), 
                                     train_X.loc[:,feature_list[:n]],train_Y, cv=5, scoring=["accuracy","f1"], return_train_score=True)
    
    mean_acc_train=np.mean(cv_results_temp["train_accuracy"])
    mean_f1_train=np.mean(cv_results_temp["train_f1"])
    mean_acc_test=np.mean(cv_results_temp["test_accuracy"])
    mean_f1_test=np.mean(cv_results_temp["test_f1"])
    
    f1_list_train.append(mean_f1_train)
    acc_list_train.append(mean_acc_train)
    f1_list_test.append(mean_f1_test)
    acc_list_test.append(mean_acc_test)
    
    cv_scoring_df=pd.DataFrame(zip(f1_list_train,f1_list_test,acc_list_train,acc_list_test))
    cv_scoring_df.columns=["Mean F1 Train","Mean F1 Test","Mean Accuracy Train","Mean Accuracy Test"]
    
    return cv_scoring_df

A for loop is created to do cross validation on decision tree using top 5 features.¶

Ensemble Learning - Adaboost¶

This section will explore using Adaboost classifier to do classification. Adaboost uses multiple decision trees and all the independent features to do classification. Next, Adaboost will identify the misclassified instances and put heavier weights on these instances to train the next decision tree on these instances. By doing so, the misclassification error can be reduced.¶

Ensemble Learning - XGBoost¶

XGBoost is another popular ensemble learning. It performs better than Adaboost for certain cases as it can:

  • randomise the tree or classifier generation which can reduce correlation among the trees or classifiers by randomly selecting the features to be used
  • penalise the trees that are rarely used
  • more hyperparameters can be trained compared to Adaboost.

Conclusison¶

Comparing the performances of the 4 models, Logistic Reg has the best performance since it has the highest F1 score in test set.¶

AdaBoost uses multiple weak classifiers to classify the instances and adjust the classifiers by putting heavier weights on misclassified instances to classify them on the next classifier, but it does not provide a clear interpretation on how the features affect the likelihood of a person uninstalling the app.¶

For a better interpretation, logistic regression provides a better interpretation as it quantifies the effect of each feature to the likelihood of a person uninstalling the app in 60 days and better performance compared to decision tree.¶

Based on the findings from logistic regression uninstalling is mainly driven by completed_games, , started_games, football, games_last_90_days, games_last_120days.¶
